#compdef pakcs
# ============================================================================
#  _pakcs — pakcs: PAKCS (Portland Aachen Kiel Curry System) —
#           Prolog-backend implementation of the CURRY language
#           (a functional + logic programming language combining
#           Haskell-syntax + Prolog-style non-determinism and
#           constraints), maintained at Christian-Albrechts-
#           Universität Kiel, Germany
#           (Michael Hanus, Bernd Brassel, et al — CAU Kiel
#           Programming Languages and Compiler Construction
#           group)
#
#  Source-direct extraction from
#    https://github.com/cau-placc/pakcs/blob/master/scripts/pakcs.sh
#      (the launcher shell script — flag handling for --help,
#      --version, --nocypm, --noreadline, --quiet + cypm/
#      frontend subcommand dispatch)
#    https://github.com/cau-placc/pakcs/blob/master/RELNOTES.md
#      (REPL command reference)
#
#  Maintained by CAU Kiel Programming Languages and Compiler
#  Construction research group (Michael Hanus — Curry language
#  designer and head researcher, Bernd Brassel, Sergio Antoy,
#  Wolfgang Lux et al, with contributions from German + US
#  academic Curry research community).  cau-placc/pakcs: 15 GH
#  stars (small academic-community repo with 30+ years of
#  ACTIVE development since the 1990s; current version 3.10.0
#  released February 2026).  PAKCS is one of two production
#  Curry implementations — the OTHER being KICS2 (Kiel Curry
#  System 2, Haskell-backend), maintained by the SAME CAU Kiel
#  team.  PAKCS uses SICStus-Prolog (recommended for performance)
#  or SWI-Prolog as its backend; programs compile via the
#  Curry-to-FlatCurry frontend, then FlatCurry-to-Prolog
#  translation, then Prolog execution.  Use cases: academic
#  research in declarative programming, constraint logic
#  programming education at Kiel/Aachen/Portland and other
#  universities, integration of Haskell-style pure functional
#  code with Prolog-style non-deterministic search.
#
#  CURRY is a functional + logic programming language designed
#  to UNIFY HASKELL-STYLE TYPED PURE FUNCTIONAL programming with
#  PROLOG-STYLE NON-DETERMINISTIC LOGIC programming.  Curry
#  programs read like Haskell — `data` declarations, pattern-
#  matching function definitions, type classes — BUT can use
#  PROLOG-STYLE features: NON-DETERMINISTIC CHOICE (multiple
#  pattern matches return all alternatives), FREE VARIABLES
#  (existentially-quantified unknowns that get unified during
#  execution), NARROWING (lazy variable instantiation), and
#  CONSTRAINT SOLVING.  Use cases: program inversion, semantic-
#  web rule engines, type-class derivation, theorem proving,
#  combinatorial optimization, and any problem domain where
#  functional + logic features compose naturally.  Sister
#  languages: haskell (in corpus + STOCK; the pure-functional
#  side that inspired Curry's syntax), prolog/swipl (in corpus
#  + STOCK; the logic-programming side that inspired Curry's
#  non-determinism), R424 Picat (logic+functional language —
#  closest related new-language entry in the corpus; Picat is
#  Curry's spiritual cousin), R429 Frege (Haskell-on-JVM — pure
#  Haskell without Curry's logic features), erlang (in corpus +
#  STOCK; pattern-matching + concurrency), mercury (in corpus
#  via _mercury — logic+functional with strong types), R427
#  Rust sericumcc (using argopt) etc.
#
#  CLI library taxonomy update: 1st Curry CLI library —
#  PAKCS's **HAND-ROLLED SH SHELL SCRIPT + C ARGV PASS-THROUGH
#  LAUNCHER**.  Curry joins the cross-language taxonomy as the
#  38th documented language.  🎉 NEW LANGUAGE entry — Curry
#  joins alongside Rust, Go, TypeScript-Node, Python, Ruby,
#  Perl, Haskell, OCaml, Elixir, R, Bash, Deno, Lua, Scheme,
#  Clojure, Common Lisp, Racket, Crystal, Nim, Zig, Odin, V,
#  Mojo, Roc, Hare, Standard ML, Erlang, Pony, Prolog, Pike,
#  F#, Janet, D, Picat, BQN, Frege, Lobster.
#
#  PAKCS's argv parser is a HYBRID — a SHELL SCRIPT WRAPPER
#  (`scripts/pakcs.sh`) intercepts certain meta-flags
#  (--help/--version/--nocypm/--noreadline/--quiet) and
#  subcommands (cypm/frontend) BEFORE handing the remaining
#  argv to the actual `$PAKCSHOME/src/pakcs` REPL binary
#  (which has its OWN parser written in Curry+Prolog for
#  REPL command handling).  Strategy:
#
